\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 15.3 Phase III \'96 Operational Execution
\fs36 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs32 \cf0 Phase III marks the transition from interrogable knowledge to executable doctrine. The institution moves beyond consultation and into structured operational conduct driven directly by encoded logic. Knowledge no longer merely answers questions; it begins to shape real decisions, enforce standards, trigger workflows, and guard against error. InternalWiki.com becomes not just an internal advisor, but the operational backbone through which institutional reasoning manifests in action.
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 1. Decision Logic Becomes Enforcement\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Rules, thresholds, sequencing, and approval gates begin to govern execution.\uc0\u8232 Underwriting covenants, procedural validations, evidence requirements, and authority checks are no longer suggestions. They are operational controls. The platform determines whether required evidence exists, whether thresholds are satisfied, whether risk tolerances are breached, and whether authority tiers have been invoked. Decisions cannot proceed if institutional logic has not been honoured.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 2. Approval Gates Embedded into Live Workflows\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Where specific actions require senior review, dual-signature clearance, specialist sign-off, or advisory input, the platform enforces the mandate.\uc0\u8232 It automatically identifies the correct approval layer, checks whether the individual has the required authority, and records the decision.\u8232 Approval becomes an act justified by logic, not a discretionary email trail.\u8232 Each gate is traceable: who approved, on what evidence, under which version of policy, and against which logic nodes.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 3. Compliance Enforcement at Point of Decision\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Regulatory constraints, licence conditions, planning rules, reporting duties, procurement thresholds, safety requirements, environmental triggers, and audit obligations are executed as logic checks.\uc0\u8232 If a mandated step is missing, if a statutory requirement applies, or if evidence thresholds fail, the platform blocks progression or demands escalation.\u8232 Compliance ceases to be retrospective audit and becomes embedded guardrails that prevent breach.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 4. Real-Time Risk Logic Application\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Institutional risk posture \'97 tolerances, ratios, conditions, exclusions, mitigation structures \'97 is applied deterministically.\uc0\u8232 The system can calculate whether a decision breaches risk appetite, whether exception pathways are available, and what mitigations are triggered by specific conditions.\u8232 Where negotiation or discretion is permissible, the platform reveals the boundary and evidential triggers that must be satisfied before deviation is justified.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 5. Procurement and Vendor Control Mechanisms\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Vendor onboarding, procurement decisions, framework selection, and due diligence steps are governed by encoded logic.\uc0\u8232 The platform enforces whether cost thresholds require board approval, whether supplier checks must be completed, whether ESG standards apply, or whether competitive tendering is mandatory.\u8232 Procurement reasoning becomes defensible and uniform.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 6. Procedural Execution and Auto-Generated Checklists\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 When staff initiate processes \'97 onboarding, due diligence, investigation, design approval, policy amendment \'97 the platform triggers procedural execution trees.\uc0\u8232 Steps appear in correct order, with evidence requirements, review conditions, authority tags, and jurisdiction notes.\u8232 Workflows no longer rely on informal checklists, inherited documents, or tribal memory.
\fs24 \

