\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 15.4 Phase IV \'96 Autonomous Policy Agents
\fs36 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f2\b0\fs32 \cf0 Phase IV introduces a controlled form of autonomy: agents capable of applying institutional logic, interpreting evidence, and drafting proposed decisions within the explicit doctrinal boundaries encoded in InternalWiki.com. These agents are not general-purpose automation tools, nor independent decision-makers. They operate strictly as policy executors and reasoning assistants, bounded by evidence-referenced knowledge nodes, lineage rules, authority tiers, and institutional epistemic standards. Their function is to scale intellectual work without diluting governance discipline.
\fs24 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa320\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 1. Institutional Doctrine as Execution Boundary\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Agents derive all reasoning from validated logic nodes: policy statements, procedural sequences, statutory interpretations, approval pathways, covenant rules, compliance triggers, jurisdiction boundaries, and evidential precedents.\uc0\u8232 They cannot invent doctrine, assert unreferenced interpretations, or apply logic outside authorised scope. If institutional knowledge is silent, ambiguous, expired, or under review, the agent escalates rather than improvises. The authority of the agent is coextensive with the clarity of the knowledge graph.
\fs24 \

