\f0\b \cf0 3. Drafting Decisions, Not Enforcing Them\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Agents generate preliminary decisions, risk assessments, approval notes, compliance clearances, underwriting recommendations, procedural step sequences, or contract term suggestions.\uc0\u8232 But execution remains contingent on human approval.\u8232 Authority is never ceded: the agent drafts; the institution decides.\u8232 As doctrinal clarity deepens, councils may define narrow domains where decisions can be auto-executed \'97 for example, procedural validations with no discretion \'97 but the principle remains: autonomy is allowed only where logic is unambiguous and risk minimal.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 4. Escalation When Doctrine is Incomplete\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 When knowledge nodes lack evidence references, exhibit contradictory logic, fall outside jurisdiction, or approach expiry, agents suspend reasoning and trigger review requests.\uc0\u8232 Rather than filling gaps with ungrounded inference, the system reveals epistemic insufficiency.\u8232 Agents become guardians of doctrinal integrity by refusing to act on weak logic.
\fs24 \

\f0\b\fs32 5. Adaptive Reasoning Within Defined Context\uc0\u8232 
\f2\b0 Agents distinguish between deterministic rules and interpretive domains.\uc0\u8232 Where a procedural step allows no discretion, the agent executes deterministically.\u8232 Where precedent reveals multiple valid interpretations, the agent surfaces the options, notes the interpretive differences, and attaches supporting evidence and lineage.\u8232 Agents recognise the epistemic landscape rather than flattening it.
\fs24 \

